    <title>Bose is adding multipoint pairing to its latest earbuds</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A photo of Bose’s Ultra Open Earbuds." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/6_CWBF_AF85HKObVzqaF6Umy_dY=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73453446/DSCF6430.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Chris Welch / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="BHaRwK"&gt;Bose is updating its two most recent pairs of earbuds, the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23883649/bose-quietcomfort-ultra-earbuds-review"&gt;QuietComfort Ultra Earbuds&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24073019/bose-ultra-open-earbuds-review"&gt;Ultra Open Earbuds&lt;/a&gt;, to add support for multipoint Bluetooth. A new software update rolling out to both products will enable them to pair with two devices at the same time for easier multitasking. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="Nw9FgC"&gt;The update, which will take a couple weeks to reach all customers, also includes a few bug fixes that are specific to Bose’s rather unique Ultra Open Earbuds. Among them are optimizations to voice pickup, overall connectivity, and a few other improvements. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="KRZ5pn"&gt;Multipoint has become a fairly common feature for premium wireless earbuds (AirPods notwithstanding), so I noted its absence as a downside in the reviews of both earbuds. Now the QC Ultra Earbuds...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
